### Step 1 — New Jinja template
Produces `[INST] … [/INST]` user turns, prepends system to the first user turn with `\n\n`, appends `eos_token` (`</s>`) after each assistant turn, and emits a single trailing space when `add_generation_prompt=true` (this becomes `inputs.generation_prompt` in the handler).

Crucially: **no `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` anywhere** — that is the sole key distinguishing marker from Ministral 3.

### Step 2 — Handler function in `common/chat.cpp`
Insert `common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3` **before** `namespace workaround` (~line 1519), after `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3`:
```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;
    data.prompt           = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format           = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.preserved_tokens = { "[INST]", "[/INST]" };
    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.prefix(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });
    data.parser = parser.save();
    return data;
}
```

### Step 3 — Detection block in `common_chat_try_specialized_template()`
Insert **before** `return std::nullopt;` (~line 1690):
```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v3 (v0.3): [INST]/[/INST] without [SYSTEM_PROMPT]
// Distinguishes from Ministral 3 by the absence of [SYSTEM_PROMPT].
if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```
**Safety:** All 4 existing templates containing `[INST]` (`Ministral-3`, `Mistral-Nemo`, `Mistral-Small-3.2`, `Devstral-Small`) also contain `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, so this condition has zero false-positive risk against current files.

